00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:17.870
medical world in this country.

00:04:17.870 --> 00:04:20.900 position:56%
So I just want to make a few remarks

00:04:20.900 --> 00:04:24.120
about publishing one's
first major book

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:29.060 position:56%
when one is a little older, as I am.

00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:35.080
It's a period of incredible
joy and a sense of plentitude.

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:39.390
That of all the people in the world
who have important stories to tell,

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:45.940 position:56%
yours gets published and is found in
a beautiful cover and has a Library

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:51.820
of Congress ISBN number and
all of those wonderful things,

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:58.780
but in addition, it was strangely
discombobulating, writing

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:01.690
and researching this
book for so long.

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:06.990
Most people know that that
can be a very lonely time,

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:09.980
but I was unprepared for the fact

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:15.460
that really publishing a book
is quite lonely, as well,

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:20.980
in that you're alone with this
baby, whom you care so much about,

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:27.190
and it's it and you, and then
suddenly, this beloved organism is

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:31.070
in the world, and you don't know
who it's with, and you don't know

00:05:31.070 --> 00:05:37.920
if it's cared for properly
and loved, and so occasions

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:43.790
like this are -- really help a
great deal in that particular sense

00:05:43.790 --> 00:05:48.860
of loneliness, because you're with
the people who have read the book

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:51.390
or will read the book and all

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:56.630
of that is really eased
in one's heart and soul.

00:05:56.630 --> 00:06:03.110
So all of which is to say
thank you again for coming.

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:10.080
Well, my hope for writing
Reading Claudius, it is both small

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.410
and contained to share a
very personal family story.

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:23.220
A kind of an elegy, a love letter
to my parents, but it's also big

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:29.850
and expansive in its own way to
inspire readers of Reading Claudius

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:35.200
to really think about how thought
and history have over all lives

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:40.920
in ways that we often don't
fully understand or recognize,

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:48.260
and most particularly, for those
of us whose parents or grandparents

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:53.080
or great-grandparents have
experienced enormous political

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:57.980
upheavals and dislocations
and sometimes threatening

00:06:57.980 --> 00:07:00.960
to destroy them, as
in my parents' case,

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:06.770
and after which must somehow
re-create their coherence,

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:11.700
their sense of themselves and
their sense of the future,

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:17.780
and in the writing of Reading
Claudius, I also recognize so fully

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:22.810
that they must've, as Gail alluded,
to the next generation and refugees

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:28.490
in America, they must also figure
out how to imagine a future

00:07:28.490 --> 00:07:30.920
for their children in a land

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:36.760
that they never anticipated raising
their children in because the land

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:42.170
that they did think would always
be theirs no longer existed.

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:48.390
So I recognize that and
adored my parents all

00:07:48.390 --> 00:07:52.790
over again with that recognition.

00:07:52.790 --> 00:07:56.670
In my own family's case,
the political trauma,

00:07:56.670 --> 00:08:01.720
the historical crisis
was World War II,

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:07.730
and what was destroyed was my
parents beloved Central Europe,

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:14.210
Prague, in their lives at the heart
of that sense of Central Europe.

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:18.800
So Reading Claudius,
as Gail mentioned,

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.760
is very much about that
former world, that lost world,

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:29.200
very much taking places in
the cafés, the coffee houses

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:37.350
that Gail alluded to, where in
that place and during that time,

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:41.590
the sense of the political and
the intellectual and the creative

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:46.540
and the artistic and the literary
were all somehow one in the same,

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:53.880 position:56%
and I think many of us long for that
kind of spirit in the United States,

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:59.640
and in the coffee houses that my
parents and uncles frequented,

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:05.450
it was always, there were day-long
and week-long, month-long debates,

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:10.400
always to the intermingling
with the smell of coffee

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:12.620
and the abundant cigarette smoke,

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:18.660
and I'm glad that Gail
mentioned how visual that was,

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:22.110
because I felt I was there, too.

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:25.100
Reading Claudius is
also about memory.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:31.350
I had a kind of an epiphany
about that, about the story being

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:34.370
about memory, when my spouse

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:41.790
and I saw the Laurie Anderson
play Homeland some years ago,

00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:46.200
just when I was in the throes
of finishing Reading Claudius,

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:52.300 position:56%
and the play opens with birds in the
sky, and it's before there is land.

00:09:52.300 --> 00:09:58.360
It's before land exists, and the
father and the mother bird die,

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:02.530
and because there's no land,
there's no place to bury them,

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:08.160
and so Laurie Anderson says,
"The daughter bird buries them

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:10.920
in the back of her head."

00:10:10.920 --> 00:10:14.380
And she says that "This is
the beginning of memory,"

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:18.590
and I was just floored by
that because I realized

00:10:18.590 --> 00:10:22.690
in writing the book that
I and probably many of us,

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:29.430
perhaps most of us, bury our
parents in the backs of our heads.

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:32.360
So Reading Claudius is about that,

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:36.240
and it's about how
all those memories

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:41.560
and meanings get communicated and
bequeathed to the next generation

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:44.660
and all that gets lost
along the way,

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:49.180
and in my case, that
was a great deal.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:56.800
So before I introduce the key
players and read a little bit,

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:00.610
many people ask me, "Why
are you writing a book

00:11:00.610 --> 00:11:05.790 position:56%
about the Emperor Claudius when this
book supposedly is about Prague?"

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:12.600
and I just want to clue you
in that it's not the Emperor.

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:16.700
Claudius in the title
refers to Matthias Claudius,

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:22.640
and old German poet,
an 18th century poet,

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:27.810
who many Central European
children were weaned on.

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:30.280
Everyone read Claudius's poems.

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:34.470
They're very simple
and quite beautiful,

00:11:34.470 --> 00:11:37.920
and I witnessed both
my mother and father

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:43.820
in the weeks before they died going
back to a little book of his poems

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:48.150
that my mother managed to
get out of Europe and read

00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:54.750
to each other Claudius' poems, and
that's what inspired the title,

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:59.830
which my editor, for a long
time, wanted to change,

00:11:59.830 --> 00:12:03.540
because she thought everyone
will be looking for the emperor,

00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:05.420
and then in the end
Reading Claudius,

00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:08.750
it had been Reading Claudius
for so long that she just,

00:12:08.750 --> 00:12:13.120
she and I both said it's got
to stay Reading Claudius.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:17.700
So that's how the title came to be.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:23.110
Well, Reading Claudius has
three starring players.

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:28.500
In part two of the book, my brother
and I become bit stars, as well,

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:35.120
but the three starring players
are my mother Leise Florsheim,

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:41.120
who came to Prague from
Frankfurt, Germany, in 1933,

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:43.910
just because Hitler
became Chancellor,

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:50.450 position:56%
because she was no longer allowed to
go onto higher education in Germany,

00:12:50.450 --> 00:12:57.600
and in Prague, she met a
fellow medical student,

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:02.110
who would later become
my father Paul Heller,

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:09.890
but while this fellow Paul Heller
developed a very quiet, shy,

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:18.920
but very big on Leise, Leise gave
her heart to Paul's older brother,

00:13:18.920 --> 00:13:24.170
Erich, who was already
kind of a literary figure

00:13:24.170 --> 00:13:31.840
and philosophy figure among the
young Jewish students in Prague.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:37.830
He was an aspiring writer
already doing some publishing

00:13:37.830 --> 00:13:42.380
and also the head of the
Socialist Student Movement.

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:50.250
So Erich became quite
prominent on the Nazi's radar,

00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:55.650
and thus began a combustible
romantic triangle

00:13:55.650 --> 00:14:01.240
that would last a lifetime and
show itself in various ways,

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:07.330
and that forms the core of the
personal story of Reading Claudius,

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:09.240
and the war itself, of course,

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:14.470
is the air that surrounds
that triangle.

00:14:14.470 --> 00:14:18.900
In late summer of 1938,
when the growing power

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:23.180
of the Nazis made it very dangerous
for German Jews to remain in Europe

00:14:23.180 --> 00:14:28.940
at all, my mother got out and
made it to the United States.

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:33.470
Some months later, my
uncle, who as I mentioned,

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:39.290
was quite a prominent
anti-Nazi, fled illegally

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:44.680
across the Polish border and made
it to safety in Cambridge, England,

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:49.910
but a short time after that, and
it was really just a matter of days

00:14:49.910 --> 00:14:55.420
after Paul's graduation from
medical school, war broke out,

00:14:55.420 --> 00:14:58.150
and Paul was arrested in
the middle of the night

00:14:58.150 --> 00:15:04.000
in the first public round up
in Prague and transported first

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.610
to Dachau then to Buchenwald,
with a year spent in Auschwitz

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:12.870
and then back to Buchenwald, and
all in all, remaining in the camps

00:15:12.870 --> 00:15:19.540
for 6 years until they
were liberated in 1945.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:23.540
In doing research for the book,
I made many trips to Europe,

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:27.530
and in one of those,
I interviewed one

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:33.360
of the remaining surviving friends
of my parents' European friends,

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:41.740
and she told me in great detail
about the Sunday afternoon when she

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:46.310
and my uncle and everyone listening
to the radio that night found

00:15:46.310 --> 00:15:53.300 position:56%
out that my father had survived, and
so I want to play a short broadcast

00:15:53.300 --> 00:16:00.740
that was part of a postscript for
the Sunday BBC News this evening

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:04.150
that no one in the group that was

00:16:04.150 --> 00:16:07.190
with Eve Adler Road [assumed
spelling] knew that this was

00:16:07.190 --> 00:16:09.530
to be aired that evening.

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:12.960
They didn't yet know
that Paul had survived.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.700
&gt;&gt; April 15, 1945.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.040
&gt;&gt; Permit me to tell you
what you would have seen

00:16:20.040 --> 00:16:22.180
and heard had you had
been with me on Thursday.

00:16:22.180 --> 00:16:24.360
It will not be pleasant listening.

00:16:24.360 --> 00:16:27.120
If you are at lunch, or
if you have no appetite

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:31.740
to hear what Germans have
done, now is a good time

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:35.040
to switch off the radio for I
propose to tell you of Buchenwald.

00:16:35.040 --> 00:16:39.240 position:56%
It is on a small hill about four
miles outside Weimar, and it was one

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:42.040
of the largest concentration
camps in Germany,

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:44.090
and it was built to last.

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:48.030
As we approached it, we saw about
a hundred men in civilian clothes

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:51.050
with rifles advancing in
open-order across the field.

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.510
There were a few shots.

00:16:52.510 --> 00:16:53.810
We stopped to inquire.

00:16:53.810 --> 00:16:56.040
We're told that some of
the prisoners had a couple

00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:58.820
of SS men cornered in there.

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:00.220
We drove on, reached the main gate.

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:04.270
The prisoners crowed
up behind the wire.

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:06.040
We entered.

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:11.530
And now, let me tell
this in the first-person,

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:13.050
for I was the least important
person there, as you can hear.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:15.370
There surged around me
an evil-smelling stink.

00:17:15.370 --> 00:17:19.070
Men and boys reached
out to touch me.

00:17:19.070 --> 00:17:21.090
They were in rags and
the remnants of uniforms.

00:17:21.090 --> 00:17:27.060
Death had already had
marked many of them,

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:28.360
but they were smiling
with their eyes.

00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:31.760
I looked out over that mass of
men to the green fields beyond,

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:35.320
where well-fed Germans
were ploughing.

00:17:35.320 --> 00:17:38.160
A German, Fritz Kersheimer,
came up and said,

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:40.170
"May I show you around the camp?

00:17:40.170 --> 00:17:41.470
I've been here for ten years."

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:45.450
An Englishman stood to attention
saying, "May I introduce myself?

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:46.750
Delighted to see you.

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:49.300
And can you tell me when some
of our folks will be along?"

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:53.040
I told him, "Soon," and asked
to see one of the barracks.

00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:56.680
It happened to be occupied
by Czechoslovakians.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:59.920 position:56%
When I entered, men crowded around,
tried to lift me to their shoulders.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:01.220
They were too weak.

00:18:01.220 --> 00:18:04.250
Many of them could
not get out of bed.

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:08.680
I was told that this building
had once stabled 80 horses.

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:12.000
There were 1200 men
in it, five to a bunk.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.860
The stink was beyond
all description.

00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:19.050
When I reached the center of the
barracks, a man came up and said,

00:18:19.050 --> 00:18:23.320
"You remember me, I am Patr
Zenkl, one time mayor of Prague."

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:26.150
I remembered him, but
did not recognize him.

00:18:26.150 --> 00:18:28.660
He asked about Benes
and Jan Masaryk.

00:18:28.660 --> 00:18:34.460 position:56%
I asked how many men had died in
that building during the last month.

00:18:34.460 --> 00:18:36.820
They called the doctor;
we inspected his records.

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:39.140
There were only names in the
little black book, nothing more --

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:42.250
nothing of who had been where,
what they had done or hoped.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:47.040
Behind the names of those who
had died there was a cross.

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.340
I counted them.

00:18:48.340 --> 00:18:54.160
They totaled 242; 242
out of 1200 in one month.

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:59.120
As I walked down to the end of
the barracks, there was applause

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:01.230
from the men too weak
to get out of bed.

00:19:01.230 --> 00:19:07.050
It sounded like the hand-clapping
of babies, they were so weak.

00:19:07.050 --> 00:19:09.990
The doctor's name was Paul Heller.

00:19:09.990 --> 00:19:11.290
He had been there since '38.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:24.720
&gt;&gt; Caroline Heller: Well I just
want to read a couple of sections,

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:29.130
short sections from the part
one and one from part two,

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:33.570
and then I hope very much
to engage in conversation

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:38.530
and invite you to ask questions.

00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:43.720
This first section takes
place in part one of the book,

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:49.110
and it takes place right after
the infamous Munich Agreement,

00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:55.440
which most of you know ceded the
Northwest part of Czechoslovakia

00:19:55.440 --> 00:20:03.110
to Hitler in order to
appease his thirst for power.

00:20:03.110 --> 00:20:07.030 position:56%
Czechoslovakia was quite weakened
by the death of its first president,

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:15.250
and Hitler took that as a moment
to set his sights on new conquests,

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:19.160
and this was all done
without the permission

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:21.010
of the new Czech President.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:24.860
It was a deal that was
negotiated by Neville Chamberlain,

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:30.060
and people who lived, Jews
and anti-Nazis who lived

00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:33.240
in the Northwest section of
Prague had to get out immediately,

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:36.740
because it would be
Nazified within 24 hours.

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:40.990
So my father, who had just
taken a day-long series

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:44.360
of medical examinations
and didn't know that all

00:20:44.360 --> 00:20:50.020
of this was happening while he was
taking his exams, stoked himself

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:56.150
on coffee and rented a cab and
went to the Northwest section

00:20:56.150 --> 00:21:02.170
of Czechoslovakia to bring his
mother and his and to safety,

00:21:02.170 --> 00:21:07.810
which was presumed to be still a
safe destination to come to Prague,

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:14.550 position:56%
and my father grew up in that
Northwest section of Czechoslovakia.

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:19.680 position:56%
When Paul arrived at 16
Welmuhlstrasse just before midnight,

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:23.870
the curtains of the Heller
family apartment were drawn.

00:21:23.870 --> 00:21:28.100
Else Heller was seated on the
sofa in the front sitting room,

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:30.420
which was lit by candles.

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:34.040
There were rumors of bombings, she
told Paul, and she'd been advised

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:36.770
to turn off all the electricity.

00:21:36.770 --> 00:21:43.080
She was dressed formally, her long
hair still jet black at 54 gathered

00:21:43.080 --> 00:21:45.590
in a bun at the back of her neck.

00:21:45.590 --> 00:21:49.770
In front of her, the marble-top
coffee table was piled with books,

00:21:49.770 --> 00:21:53.660
clothes, and open boxes of
photographs and letters.

00:21:53.660 --> 00:21:57.740
On the floor next to her sat
her suitcase and handbag.

00:21:57.740 --> 00:22:03.100 position:56%
She was clutching a small paper bowl
laminated with pictures of sea birds

00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:06.550
that Erich had made for
her when he was a boy.

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:09.950
"You have to put candy in it in
order for it to be balanced,"

00:22:09.950 --> 00:22:12.250
she said as she looked up at Paul.

00:22:12.250 --> 00:22:13.990
Her face ashen.

00:22:13.990 --> 00:22:18.530 position:56%
"Kind of like me," Paul said, trying
to bring lightness to his voice

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:22.000
to avoid frightening
his mother any further.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.430
"I must tell you that
cousin Fanny had yesterday,

00:22:25.430 --> 00:22:28.370
out of the blue, a
tonsils operation."

00:22:28.370 --> 00:22:31.630
she went on, making
conversation, as she always did

00:22:31.630 --> 00:22:33.880
when she was nervous and upset.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:38.040
Lana and Carl came by and told
me she was in the hospital.

00:22:38.040 --> 00:22:39.340
"The cab is waiting.

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:40.830
Mother, we must go."

00:22:40.830 --> 00:22:44.440
"Do you remember when Erich cut
his finger making this bowl?"

00:22:44.440 --> 00:22:48.520
she asked, running her hand
across its bumpy, varnished edge.

00:22:48.520 --> 00:22:51.990
"He made a frightful fuss,
a most terrible fuss.

00:22:51.990 --> 00:22:53.760
Do you remember that?"

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:56.380
Else's eyes were cavernous.

00:22:56.380 --> 00:22:59.760
"Mother, you'll feel better
once you're in the cab."

00:22:59.760 --> 00:23:03.460
"You must let me decide how
I feel," she said sharply.

00:23:03.460 --> 00:23:05.660
"I didn't have time
to withdraw money.

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:07.790 position:56%
I haven't selected what I must take.

00:23:07.790 --> 00:23:10.430
I haven't sorted through
father's books.

00:23:10.430 --> 00:23:11.790
I cannot go.

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:13.450
Perhaps tomorrow."

00:23:13.450 --> 00:23:18.270
She sat stiff and delicate,
her coat draped over her lap.

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:20.780 position:56%
"Mother, we can do that from Prague.

00:23:20.780 --> 00:23:22.270
Anny can help us.

00:23:22.270 --> 00:23:24.100
She can send things.

00:23:24.100 --> 00:23:26.180
Else's eyes roamed over the room,

00:23:26.180 --> 00:23:29.100
turning to the open
boxes on the table.

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:32.130
She fingered Erich's
paper bowl again.

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:33.590
"Have you eaten?"

00:23:33.590 --> 00:23:34.890
Paul nodded.

00:23:34.890 --> 00:23:37.710
"But you'll have a bite
of something with me, no?"

00:23:37.710 --> 00:23:39.470
"We haven't the time, mother.

00:23:39.470 --> 00:23:42.350
We'll eat at Mina's."

00:23:42.350 --> 00:23:44.370
He stood motionless in front of her

00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:47.850
for several moments then
moved toward where she sat.

00:23:47.850 --> 00:23:49.830
"Mother, we must leave.

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:51.220
We must go now.

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:53.220
Please let me help you."

00:23:53.220 --> 00:23:58.450
He spoke in a stern and unequivocal
he'd never used with her.

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:01.410
He felt the blood go to
the back of his neck.

00:24:01.410 --> 00:24:05.810
Else Heller was a tiny
woman, standing under 5 feet,

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:08.850
but over that height,
she was solidly built.

00:24:08.850 --> 00:24:12.720
Paul put his had over her
forearm, but she rose on her own,

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:14.820
went down the hall to the kitchen,

00:24:14.820 --> 00:24:17.810
and came back carrying
the silver butter mold

00:24:17.810 --> 00:24:21.230
that Alfred's parents had
given them at their wedding.

00:24:21.230 --> 00:24:24.990
She added it, along with the
bowl, to one of the boxes,

00:24:24.990 --> 00:24:29.290
applied a few drops of cologne
from a bottle in her handbag,

00:24:29.290 --> 00:24:32.080 position:56%
and stooped to blow out the candles.

00:24:32.080 --> 00:24:36.490
Without looking at Paul, she laced
her arm in his and let him lead her

00:24:36.490 --> 00:24:41.630
down the steps and out the door
into the drizzly open night.

00:24:41.630 --> 00:24:43.960
The street, which rarely
saw traffic,

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:46.750
was filled with cars and taxicabs.

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:51.190
The route to Ida's
apartment took them past Paul

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:54.740
and Erich's gymnasium, and
the candle-lit apartment

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:58.970 position:56%
where the parents of Paul's
childhood friend, Camillo Fleischer,

00:24:58.970 --> 00:25:03.440
the only other Jewish boy in
his gymnasium class, lived.

00:25:03.440 --> 00:25:07.100
He wondered what Camillo and
his family were planning to do.

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:11.170
The taxi climbed the hill
past the Komatau Kino

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:14.460
and the music hall were Paul
and Erich had taken part

00:25:14.460 --> 00:25:16.080
in the children's theater,

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:20.040
and Dr. Fleishman had
conducted the Komatau Orchestra

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:25.580
and continued past Bobby Komisch's
haberdashery, Mendel's Bookstore,

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:30.400
then across the railroad bridge
and past the old iron ore quarry.

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:31.970
All until that night,

00:25:31.970 --> 00:25:36.460
the unquestioned constants
in Paul's life.

00:25:36.460 --> 00:25:40.660
Tante Ida was waiting in the
alcove doorway of her building,

00:25:40.660 --> 00:25:43.500
a small suitcase by her side.

00:25:43.500 --> 00:25:44.970
She was dressed warmly.

00:25:44.970 --> 00:25:47.660
The the tight-laced
collar she always wore

00:25:47.660 --> 00:25:52.350
to Saturday services
visible under her jacket.

00:25:52.350 --> 00:25:54.780
"Du Bist so tuchtig, Pauli."

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:58.980
the diminutive 68-year-old
said in the authoritative tone

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:01.670
in which she issued
all her judgments.

00:26:01.670 --> 00:26:05.730
It was the highest accolade one
could receive from Tante Ida.

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:09.870
Levelheaded, able to
get things done.

00:26:09.870 --> 00:26:13.930
Paul put her bag next to his
mother's on the front seat.

00:26:13.930 --> 00:26:17.730
The two women sat in back
on either side of Paul

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:22.080
in their rain-moist fur jackets,
their small spectacles glinting

00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:26.100
in all directions as the cab
followed traffic toward the main

00:26:26.100 --> 00:26:32.870
road for what was usually a
two hour ride back to Prague

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:35.720
but likely would take
far longer tonight.

00:26:35.720 --> 00:26:38.950
The windows were open just
enough to let the smells

00:26:38.950 --> 00:26:41.800
of exhaust and wet pavement in.

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:44.250
The honking and screeching
of brakes in the middle

00:26:44.250 --> 00:26:47.400
of the night had a surreal quality.

00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:51.360
Else loosened the laces
on her shoes.

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.540
Through the rear-view
mirror, Paul could see

00:26:53.540 --> 00:26:58.010
in the distance the dim lights of
other [inaudible] towns nestled

00:26:58.010 --> 00:27:00.110
at the foot of the mountains.

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:02.920
No one exhaled a normal breath.

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:07.800
The only words came from the taxi
driver, who talked about God.

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:12.080
That day he'd become
convinced for an absolute fact

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.790
that there was none, he said.

00:27:14.790 --> 00:27:18.300
In the silence, he made
weak, worried jokes.

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.060
"How can anyone take
the Nazis seriously?

00:27:21.060 --> 00:27:22.730
They march too much."

00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:26.970
Just before dawn, as
the rain was ending,

00:27:26.970 --> 00:27:30.390
they arrived at Walter
and Mina's apartment.

00:27:30.390 --> 00:27:35.440
Grandma Mina, whose sense of humor
was legendary, poured hot coffee

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:39.300
from a silver earn the
sputtered more than flowed.

00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:42.120
"My ribald friends
regard this coffee pot

00:27:42.120 --> 00:27:44.210
as having prostate trouble.

00:27:44.210 --> 00:27:45.510
It has a problem.

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:47.700
It has a problem."

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:50.250
she declared with a
great heave of a laugh,

00:27:50.250 --> 00:27:55.250
pretending like the taxi driver and
like Paul to a sense of normalcy

00:27:55.250 --> 00:27:57.380
that she surely did not feel.

00:27:57.380 --> 00:28:01.120
She poured thick, pulpy
orange juice, which Paul,

00:28:01.120 --> 00:28:04.320
awakening to his body for the
first time since he'd walked

00:28:04.320 --> 00:28:08.560
out of the examination
hall over 15 hours before,

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:13.440
drank with such voraciousness,
that it dribbled over his chin.

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:18.220 position:56%
As the sun came up, Mina enlisted
Else and Ida's advice on the cooking

00:28:18.220 --> 00:28:22.730
of eggs for their breakfast
and a debate, led by Tante Ida,

00:28:22.730 --> 00:28:26.230
about the best way
to fry them followed.

00:28:26.230 --> 00:28:31.150
That night, instead of returning
to his dormitory, Paul collapsed

00:28:31.150 --> 00:28:35.600
on the sofa in the room that his
mother and aunt now occupied,

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:39.730
listening to their short,
shallow breaths as they slept.

00:28:39.730 --> 00:28:43.940
The world, which for so long
in his mind had looked one way,

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:49.000 position:56%
had begun to look totally different.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:29:00.110
Well, I want to take you from
Prague to Riverside, Illinois,

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:05.310
which is jarring, believe me.

00:29:05.310 --> 00:29:09.040
[laughter] This is a
section from part two.

00:29:09.040 --> 00:29:14.470
Part two was called the Unthought
Known, which implies the degree

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:18.960
to which children know
what they don't know.

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:23.850
They absorb something that
they don't realize they know,

00:29:23.850 --> 00:29:27.180
and this little section
is called The Brick,

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:34.900 position:56%
and it is about that moment when I
knew something I didn't know I knew.

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:39.750
I became a shark in
the summer of 1957,

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:41.710
just months after I'd been sick.

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:46.030
I had encephalitis when I was
a little girl and it came right

00:29:46.030 --> 00:29:50.250
after this, or I was
sick right before this.

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:53.780
I'd begun that summer as
a minnow, and then along

00:29:53.780 --> 00:29:57.510
with another 7-year-old girl,
having made the most progress

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:00.270
in the Riverside Summer
Swimming Program,

00:30:00.270 --> 00:30:03.210
was promoted to the rank of shark.

00:30:03.210 --> 00:30:07.140
I walked through the
corridor of mandatory showers,

00:30:07.140 --> 00:30:11.640
my bare feet slapping the puddles
gathering on the tiles and stood

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:16.200
for a moment in the arched entrance
to the pool where the still water

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:19.790
and the clean, cold
air felt otherworldly.

00:30:19.790 --> 00:30:23.630
Today, the last day of the
summer season, my mother would be

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:26.610
in the bleachers watching me.

00:30:26.610 --> 00:30:30.740
After the minnows, fish, and
flying fish performed their kicks

00:30:30.740 --> 00:30:34.830
and strokes, wrapped themselves in
towels, and joined their families

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:40.040
in the bleachers, the sharks lined
up along the deep end and dived in,

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:42.250
swimming two lengths of the pool

00:30:42.250 --> 00:30:46.800
in the hushed peacefulness
of the water.

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:53.510 position:56%
The feel and sound of my sturdy,
rhythmic strokes filled me with joy.

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:57.390
At the end of our laps, the
athletic director, Mr. Perkins,

00:30:57.390 --> 00:31:01.240
his sports medallion shimmering
in his dark chest hair,

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:04.680
grabbed the microphone he
used for just to this day

00:31:04.680 --> 00:31:06.730
and announced my name and that

00:31:06.730 --> 00:31:10.590
of the other little girl whose
swimming had most improved.

00:31:10.590 --> 00:31:13.700
He knelt down between
us as he explained.

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:17.140
The words amplified through
his microphone that both

00:31:17.140 --> 00:31:18.870
of us would dive into the deep end

00:31:18.870 --> 00:31:23.150
and whoever retrieved the 3-pound
rubber brick from the bottom

00:31:23.150 --> 00:31:29.330 position:56%
of the pool would be the 1957 summer
champion and receive a trophy.

00:31:29.330 --> 00:31:32.880
After that moment, I have no
memory of the other little girl.

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:39.030
I dived in, the cold water seeping
on the edge of my bathing cap

00:31:39.030 --> 00:31:41.410
as my arms and hands pulled my body

00:31:41.410 --> 00:31:44.620
down toward the shed
we dark object below.

00:31:44.620 --> 00:31:49.740
I took firm hold of the brick in my
left hand, allowing my stronger arm

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:54.710
and hand to power me to the
surface of the pool and my triumph.

00:31:54.710 --> 00:31:58.840 position:56%
Mr. Perkins pulled me from the water
and held up the black rubber brick

00:31:58.840 --> 00:32:02.110
to the audience as the
emblem of my victory.

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:06.490
To a loud current of applause
coming from the bleachers,

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:09.230
he then presented me with a trophy.

00:32:09.230 --> 00:32:12.160 position:56%
A small golden girl with a tiny face

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:14.960
of barely discernible
features standing

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:18.660
on a vanilla-white
pedestal poised to dive.

00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:22.640
My pride was so great
it was almost painful.

00:32:22.640 --> 00:32:26.050
Scrunching my eyes against the
light coming through the windows

00:32:26.050 --> 00:32:29.860
above the bleachers, I
found my mother's face.

00:32:29.860 --> 00:32:34.740
She was glancing right, then
left, as if seeking confirmation

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.890
from the mothers sitting around her

00:32:36.890 --> 00:32:39.850
that this great event
had really happened.

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:44.830
When she looked toward me,
her face was awash in tears.

00:32:44.830 --> 00:32:46.820
Even as in a separate corner

00:32:46.820 --> 00:32:50.200
of my mind I replayed
every thrilling stroke

00:32:50.200 --> 00:32:53.530
that have propelled me from
the bottom of the pool, now,

00:32:53.530 --> 00:32:57.060
seeing my mother's face,
I could scarcely breathe.

00:32:57.060 --> 00:32:59.570
Her tears seemed earthshaking,

00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:03.410
as if my performance had
represented the clear condition

00:33:03.410 --> 00:33:05.860
of everything she needed.

00:33:05.860 --> 00:33:09.490
Before my dive, I hadn't known
that I possessed the strength

00:33:09.490 --> 00:33:12.830
that had won me this
prize, and now in a flash,

00:33:12.830 --> 00:33:18.120
I felt my own realization taken
from me, engulfed by the intensity

00:33:18.120 --> 00:33:22.650
of my mother's emotion before
I could claim it as my own.

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:25.100
Trying to hold myself tall,

00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:31.240
to step back into the exultation
I'd felt a moment before,

00:33:31.240 --> 00:33:35.220
I smiled at her, but
what I'd felt was gone.

00:33:35.220 --> 00:33:38.590
Replacing my pride
came in anguish deeper

00:33:38.590 --> 00:33:41.090
than anything I had words for.

00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:45.950
Achingly devoted to her, I did
not have it in my power to think,

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:49.790
much less to say, "I'm
not really the strong.

00:33:49.790 --> 00:33:52.440
I will not always be
able to do this.

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:54.610
I will disappoint you."

00:33:54.610 --> 00:33:58.230
It was the first time I
remember wanting to go backward

00:33:58.230 --> 00:34:02.300
into tininess, into invisibility.

00:34:02.300 --> 00:34:07.360
On the drive home, my thighs damp
against the hot vinyl car seat,

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:11.110
my trophy lying on the seat
between my mother and me,

00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:14.130
the responsibility I
felt to make her happy,

00:34:14.130 --> 00:34:19.350
to make both my parents proud,
was too great for my body to hold.

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:25.000
I started to cry so hard
that my nose began to bleed.

00:34:34.210 --> 00:34:39.040
Well, I know it's kind of hard
to come back from being in Prague

00:34:39.040 --> 00:34:44.330
and in the high school swimming
pool with me to asking questions

00:34:44.330 --> 00:34:49.780
and conversation, but I really
enjoy that part of this.

00:34:49.780 --> 00:34:54.940
So please do feel free
to comment or question.

00:34:54.940 --> 00:34:56.240
Gail?

