00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:44.890
from Random House,
crazy good fortune.

00:51:44.890 --> 00:51:51.680
So I had to write the book,
but that certainly doesn't mean

00:51:51.680 --> 00:51:54.450
that it was in any way easy.

00:51:54.450 --> 00:51:58.350
I alluded to it with Phyllis's
question about how difficult

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:03.150
that center portion was, and
the whole thing, you know,

00:52:03.150 --> 00:52:07.010
the center portion, when I read
my father's death march diary,

00:52:07.010 --> 00:52:12.150
and I had read it many times,
it was as though someone were,

00:52:12.150 --> 00:52:16.030
for the first time, telling
me this is what your dad --

00:52:16.030 --> 00:52:18.800
it was as though I never
knew anything about it,

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:24.510
the degree to which it absolutely
undid me, what he went through,

00:52:24.510 --> 00:52:29.660
and I just -- I thought there
was something wrong with me

00:52:29.660 --> 00:52:34.670
that I would be, you know, be
willing to go into that darkness,

00:52:34.670 --> 00:52:40.030
but it was also so
compelling to do so.

00:52:40.030 --> 00:52:42.670
So it was very hard.

00:52:42.670 --> 00:52:45.720
It was very hard to
write about myself.

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.020
This is something.

00:52:47.020 --> 00:52:50.580
Part two is all the
idea of my editor.

00:52:50.580 --> 00:52:55.250
I thought I was done about five
years, four years before I was done

00:52:55.250 --> 00:52:59.470
because it's like here's the
story of my parents, and no.

00:52:59.470 --> 00:53:00.770
You have to be in it.

00:53:00.770 --> 00:53:03.690
I think it makes it
a much better book,

00:53:03.690 --> 00:53:07.020
but I never anticipated
telling my story.

00:53:07.020 --> 00:53:10.820
I never anticipated
coming out to the world.

00:53:10.820 --> 00:53:18.000
It's just the things one does
that the sort of the momentum

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:22.450
of the words just suddenly you're
in a position where you have

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:25.580
to do something that you
didn't anticipate doing

00:53:25.580 --> 00:53:29.890
because the story matters
suddenly so much to you.

00:53:33.210 --> 00:53:34.510
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:53:34.510 --> 00:53:35.940
&gt;&gt; Caroline Heller: Anything else?

00:53:35.940 --> 00:53:37.270
&gt;&gt; I have one.

00:53:37.270 --> 00:53:39.930
Did your parents ever
visit Czechoslovakia?

00:53:39.930 --> 00:53:43.510
&gt;&gt; Caroline Heller: Yes, they
did, and I was with them.

00:53:43.510 --> 00:53:45.820
It was in 1982.

00:53:45.820 --> 00:53:50.510
It was still under communist
rule, and it was very emotional.

00:53:50.510 --> 00:53:58.230
My father crazily was detained in
the airport because in that myopia

00:53:58.230 --> 00:54:03.100
of the new regime, the
communist regime basically,

00:54:03.100 --> 00:54:04.400
Hitler never happened.

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:11.260
It was never -- and he, according
to the police, the airport police,

00:54:11.260 --> 00:54:18.230
they had no reasonable record of
why my father left Czechoslovakia,

00:54:18.230 --> 00:54:26.370
and he was so pale when
he came out of that room.

00:54:26.370 --> 00:54:36.100 position:56%
It was so difficult, so strange, but
that was the worst part of the trip.

00:54:36.100 --> 00:54:40.000
Then it was just incredible
to be with my parents,

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.460
and my mother took me
to the coffeehouses.

00:54:42.460 --> 00:54:43.800
Many of them are gone.

00:54:43.800 --> 00:54:47.660
Some aren't, and to be able to do

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:50.170
that with my parents
was just amazing,

00:54:50.170 --> 00:54:53.130
and my mother got sick
shortly thereafter.

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:55.320
So it was such a gift.

00:54:55.320 --> 00:54:56.620
&gt;&gt; The house survived?

00:54:56.620 --> 00:54:58.660
They visit that place
where used to live?

00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:00.660
&gt;&gt; Caroline Heller: My
father visited his house,

00:55:00.660 --> 00:55:02.330
and there was still his apartment.

00:55:02.330 --> 00:55:07.030
There was still a little -- you
could see the imprint of the plaque

00:55:07.030 --> 00:55:11.690
that had said -- his Dr.
Alfred Heller, and it was --

00:55:11.690 --> 00:55:13.790
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:55:13.790 --> 00:55:19.260
&gt;&gt; Gail Shirazi: Well, I'd
like to thank you for coming.

00:55:19.260 --> 00:55:21.060
&gt;&gt; Caroline Heller:
Thank you so much.

00:55:21.060 --> 00:55:34.960
[ Applause ]

00:55:34.960 --> 00:55:38.050
&gt;&gt; Gail Shirazi: And if anybody
wants to buy copies of the book,

00:55:38.050 --> 00:55:41.160
they're being sold outside,
and Caroline, I'm sure,

00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:43.780
would love to sign them,
and it's really a treat

00:55:43.780 --> 00:55:48.250
to have an author come
and talk about her book,

00:55:48.250 --> 00:55:49.800
and it was a wonderful book.

00:55:49.800 --> 00:55:51.100
Thank you.

00:55:51.100 --> 00:55:52.790
Thank you for writing it.

00:55:52.790 --> 00:55:54.590
Thank you.

